<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE STATE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Five black girls who failed to make the Palm Springs High School varsity 
cheerleading squad have sued the school, its principal and the Palm Springs 
Unified School District, alleging that they were passed over because of their 
race. The federal court suit charges that "racism is common" on the campus and 
that scoring during tryouts for 16 spots was tailored to favor white students. 
Represented by attorney Gloria Allred, the girls -- Aneka Knight, Carla 
Johnston, Elizabeth Williams, Tisha Pollard and Joy Brown -- ask the court to 
direct the district to cease its allegedly discriminatory practices and allow 
them to join the team in time for training camp in August. District officials 
would not comment on the suit but said a Board of Education investigation found 
no evidence of discrimination. 
</P>
