</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
M1 Retreats, M2 Rises: The narrowest measure of the nation's money supply, M1, 
fell in the week ended June 19, to a seasonally adjusted $768.3 billion from a 
revised $769.6 billion, the Federal Reserve Board reported. A broader measure, 
known as M2, rose to a seasonally adjusted $3,092.9 billion from a revised 
$3,088.6 billion the week before. M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in 
checking accounts and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like 
savings deposits and money-market mutual funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
